Is there any situation in which multiple assertions per test can be 
justified? For example, talking to an expensive external resource that 
can&#39;t easily be mocked (e.g. third party hardware)?
--
Stephen Smith, MEng (Wales).
http://www.stephen-smith.co.uk/

J. B. Rainsberger wrote:
&gt; Chaudhary, Harsh wrote:
&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Is there a way in jUnit to override the failfast behavior e.g. my code
&gt;&gt; looks like:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; public void testOrder() {
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; assertEquals(9, Largest.largest(new int[] {9,8,7}));
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; assertEquals(44, Largest.largest(new int[] {8,9,7}));
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; assertEquals(32, Largest.largest(new int[] {7,8,9}));
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; }
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; I know the 2nd and 3rd asserts would fail. I want to see both results as
&gt;&gt; having failed in my results. But jUnit just stops at the first failure.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Is there any way to change this behavior?
&gt; 
&gt; This is a FAQ. Google &quot;JUnit multiple assertions per test&quot;. I explain 
&gt; the reasons why JUnit isn&#39;t built this way in _JUnit Recipes_ and a 
&gt; number of us have re-written that answer dozens of times in this mailing 
&gt; list, so check the archives.
&gt; 
&gt; The short version: No, you can&#39;t, and you shouldn&#39;t, because those are 3 
&gt; different tests.
&gt; 
&gt; For the longer version, search the web.
&gt; 
&gt; Take care.
